The `PlaceAutocompleteElement` is the modern web component replacement for the older `Autocomplete` widget. You append it to the DOM directly, then listen for the `gmp-placeselect` event, which fires when the user picks a suggestion. The selected place object then needs its fields fetched explicitly via `fetchFields()` [Source 1, Source 2].

Here's a full working example:

```javascript
async function initAutocomplete() {
  // Load the places library
  const { PlaceAutocompleteElement } = await google.maps.importLibrary("places");
  const { Map } = await google.maps.importLibrary("maps");

  const map = new Map(document.getElementById("map"), {
    center: { lat: 40.7128, lng: -74.0060 },
    zoom: 12,
    mapId: "YOUR_MAP_ID",
  });

  // Create the autocomplete element
  const placeAutocomplete = new google.maps.places.PlaceAutocompleteElement({
    componentRestrictions: { country: "us" }, // Optional: restrict to a country
  });

  // Attach it to your search container in the DOM
  document.getElementById("search-container").appendChild(placeAutocomplete);

  // Listen for a place selection
  placeAutocomplete.addEventListener("gmp-placeselect", async (event) => {
    const place = event.place;

    // Fetch only the fields you need (field masking controls billing)
    await place.fetchFields({
      fields: ["displayName", "location", "formattedAddress"],
    });

    console.log("Name:", place.displayName);
    console.log("Address:", place.formattedAddress);
    console.log("Coords:", place.location.lat(), place.location.lng());

    // Pan the map to the selected place
    map.setCenter(place.location);
    map.setZoom(15);
  });
}

initAutocomplete();
```

And the corresponding HTML:

```html
<div id="search-container"></div>
<div id="map" style="height: 500px;"></div>
```

A few things worth noting:

- **Field masking matters for billing** — only request the fields you actually need in `fetchFields()`. Each field group has a different billing SKU [Source 2].
- **`gmp-placeselect` vs `place_changed`** — the older `Autocomplete` widget uses `place_changed`; `PlaceAutocompleteElement` uses `gmp-placeselect`. Don't mix them up.
- **The place isn't fully populated on selection** — you must call `await place.fetchFields(...)` before accessing place properties; the event only gives you a place reference, not full data [Source 1].

**Sources:**
- [Places API (New) and Autocomplete](https://developers.google.com/maps/documentation/places/web-service/overview)

Based on the retrieved documentation, here are the Google Maps Platform deprecations explicitly covered in the 2026 migration guide:

---

## 1. `google.maps.Marker` → `AdvancedMarkerElement`

The legacy `Marker` class is deprecated. The replacement is `AdvancedMarkerElement`, which offers better performance, accessibility, custom HTML content support, and improved collision handling [Source 1].

**Key migration requirements:**
- Add a `mapId` to your `Map` constructor
- Explicitly import the `marker` library
- Replace the `icon` property with an HTML `content` property for custom icons

```javascript
// OLD (deprecated)
const marker = new google.maps.Marker({
  position: { lat: 40.7128, lng: -74.0060 },
  map,
  title: "NYC",
  icon: "custom-icon.png",
});

// NEW (recommended)
const { AdvancedMarkerElement } = await google.maps.importLibrary("marker");
const marker = new AdvancedMarkerElement({
  position: { lat: 40.7128, lng: -74.0060 },
  map,
  title: "NYC",
});
```

---

## 2. Legacy Places API (`PlacesService`) → Places API (New)

The callback-based `PlacesService` is being replaced by the promise-based `Place` class [Source 1, Source 3].

**Key changes:**
- `PlacesService.getDetails()` → `Place.fetchFields()`
- `PlacesService.findPlaceFromQuery()` → `Place.searchByText()`
- `PlacesService.nearbySearch()` → `Place.searchNearby()`
- Required field masking (you only pay for fields you request)

```javascript
// OLD (legacy)
const service = new google.maps.places.PlacesService(map);
service.getDetails(
  { placeId: "ChIJ...", fields: ["name", "geometry"] },
  (place, status) => {
    if (status === google.maps.places.PlacesServiceStatus.OK) {
      console.log(place.name);
    }
  }
);

// NEW (recommended)
const { Place } = await google.maps.importLibrary("places");
const place = new Place({ id: "ChIJ..." });
await place.fetchFields({ fields: ["displayName", "location"] });
console.log(place.displayName);
```

---

## 3. Inline Map Styles (`styles` array) → Cloud-Based Styling

Passing a `styles` array directly to the `Map` constructor is deprecated. The recommended approach is Cloud-based styling via a Map ID [Source 1, Source 2].

**Benefits of switching:**
- Update styles without code changes
- A/B test different styles
- Consistent styling across web, Android, and iOS
- Better performance (styles applied server-side)

```javascript
// OLD — inline styles array (deprecated)
const map = new google.maps.Map(element, {
  styles: [
    { featureType: "water", stylers: [{ color: "#004358" }] },
  ],
});

// NEW — Cloud-based styling via Map ID
const map = new google.maps.Map(element, {
  mapId: "YOUR_MAP_ID",
});
```

---

## General Advice for Staying Current

The docs recommend these practices to avoid being caught off guard by future deprecations [Source 2]:
- Subscribe to the Google Maps Platform blog
- Check the deprecation schedule quarterly
- Use `v: "weekly"` or `v: "quarterly"` to stay on a recent API version
- Monitor browser console warnings — deprecated features log warnings before removal

---

