- [Places API (New) and Autocomplete](https://developers.google.com/maps/documentation/places/web-service/overview)
- [Maps JavaScript API Overview](https://developers.google.com/maps/documentation/javascript/overview)

Loading the Maps JavaScript API in a React app requires some care to avoid common pitfalls like re-renders and SSR issues. Here's the recommended approach:

## Option 1: `@googlemaps/js-api-loader` (Recommended)

Use the official loader package, which handles script injection cleanly and works well with React's lifecycle:

```javascript
import { useEffect, useRef } from "react";
import { Loader } from "@googlemaps/js-api-loader";

export default function MapComponent() {
  const mapRef = useRef(null);
  const mapInstanceRef = useRef(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    // Only initialize once
    if (mapRef.current && !mapInstanceRef.current) {
      const loader = new Loader({
        apiKey: "YOUR_API_KEY",
        version: "weekly",
      });

      loader.importLibrary("maps").then(({ Map }) => {
        mapInstanceRef.current = new Map(mapRef.current, {
          center: { lat: 40.7128, lng: -74.0060 },
          zoom: 12,
          mapId: "YOUR_MAP_ID", // Required for AdvancedMarkerElement
        });
      });
    }
  }, []);

  return <div ref={mapRef} style={{ width: "100%", height: "400px" }} />;
}
```

## Option 2: Dynamic Import in Next.js

If you're using Next.js, the Maps API requires `window`, which doesn't exist during server-side rendering. Wrap your map component with a dynamic import [Source 5]:

```javascript
// pages/index.js
import dynamic from "next/dynamic";

const MapComponent = dynamic(() => import("../components/MapComponent"), {
  ssr: false,
  loading: () => <div>Loading map...</div>,
});

export default function Home() {
  return <MapComponent />;
}
```

## Key Patterns to Follow

- **Use `useRef` + `useEffect`** to initialize the map only once and avoid re-creating it on every render [Source 5].
- **Store the map instance in a `useRef`**, not `useState` — updating state triggers re-renders, which you don't want.
- **Clean up event listeners** on unmount to prevent memory leaks [Source 5]:

```javascript
useEffect(() => {
  const listener = mapInstanceRef.current?.addListener("click", handleClick);
  return () => {
    if (listener) google.maps.event.removeListener(listener);
  };
}, [mapInstanceRef.current]);
```

- **Use `importLibrary()`** to load only what you need (`"maps"`, `"marker"`, `"places"`, etc.) rather than loading everything upfront [Source 1].

**Sources:**
- [Maps JavaScript API Overview](https://developers.google.com/maps/documentation/javascript/overview)
- [Common Errors and Troubleshooting](https://developers.google.com/maps/documentation/javascript/error-messages)

The Directions API and Routes API serve the same core purpose — calculating routes between locations — but the Routes API is the modern replacement with several meaningful improvements [Source 1, Source 5].

Here's a breakdown of the key differences:

| Capability | Directions API (Legacy) | Routes API (New) |
|---|---|---|
| Field masking | ❌ Not supported | ✅ Required (pay only for what you use) |
| Traffic modeling | Basic | Improved, with `TRAFFIC_AWARE_OPTIMAL` option |
| Toll information | ❌ | ✅ |
| Two-wheeler routing | ❌ | ✅ |
| Polyline quality options | ❌ | ✅ |
| Pricing tiers | Flat | SKU-based on routing preference |

One important nuance: **the split depends on where you're routing** [Source 5]:

- **Server-side routing** → Migrate to the Routes API REST endpoint (`POST https://routes.googleapis.com/directions/v2:computeRoutes`)
- **Client-side routing** (in the browser, with a rendered map) → The Maps JavaScript API's `DirectionsService` and `DirectionsRenderer` **remain the recommended approach** and are not deprecated

So if you're currently using `DirectionsService` in your frontend code, you don't need to migrate anything. If you're making server-side route calculations via the REST Directions API, the Routes API is the recommended path forward.

### Routes API REST Example

```javascript
// Server-side: POST to Routes API
const response = await fetch("https://routes.googleapis.com/directions/v2:computeRoutes", {
  method: "POST",
  headers: {
    "Content-Type": "application/json",
    "X-Goog-Api-Key": "YOUR_API_KEY",
    // Field mask controls what's returned AND what you're billed for
    "X-Goog-FieldMask": "routes.duration,routes.distanceMeters,routes.polyline.encodedPolyline",
  },
  body: JSON.stringify({
    origin: { location: { latLng: { latitude: 40.7128, longitude: -74.0060 } } },
    destination: { location: { latLng: { latitude: 34.0522, longitude: -118.2437 } } },
    travelMode: "DRIVE",
    routingPreference: "TRAFFIC_AWARE",
  }),
});

const data = await response.json();
console.log(data.routes[0].duration);
console.log(data.routes[0].distanceMeters);
```

### Client-Side DirectionsService (Still Recommended)

```javascript
const directionsService = new google.maps.DirectionsService();
const directionsRenderer = new google.maps.DirectionsRenderer();

directionsRenderer.setMap(map);

directionsService.route(
  {
    origin: "New York, NY",
    destination: "Boston, MA",
    travelMode: google.maps.TravelMode.DRIVING,
  },
  (result, status) => {
    if (status === google.maps.DirectionsStatus.OK) {
      directionsRenderer.setDirections(result);
    } else {
      console.error("Directions request failed:", status);
    }
  }
);
```

**Sources:**
- [Routes API and Directions](https://developers.google.com/maps/documentation/routes/overview)
- [Deprecations and Migration Guide](https://developers.google.com/maps/deprecations)

The `OVER_QUERY_LIMIT` error means you've exceeded either your queries-per-second (QPS) or daily quota limit for the API you're calling [Source 2]. It can also appear when you exceed the 25-waypoint limit for the Directions API, though that's a separate `MAX_WAYPOINTS_EXCEEDED` error [Source 5].

There are a few ways to resolve it:

1. **Implement exponential backoff** — retry failed requests with increasing delays
2. **Batch requests** where possible to reduce total call volume
3. **Check your quota** in Cloud Console > APIs & Services > Quotas
4. **Request a quota increase** if your legitimate usage consistently hits the limit

Here's a retry implementation with exponential backoff [Source 2]:

```javascript
async function geocodeWithRetry(address, retries = 3) {
  for (let i = 0; i < retries; i++) {
    try {
      const result = await geocoder.geocode({ address });
      return result;
    } catch (error) {
      if (error.code === "OVER_QUERY_LIMIT" && i < retries - 1) {
        // Wait 1s, then 2s, then 4s before each retry
        await new Promise(resolve => setTimeout(resolve, Math.pow(2, i) * 1000));
        continue;
      }
      throw error;
    }
  }
}
```

If you're hitting quota limits regularly, also consider setting **daily quota caps** per API in the Cloud Console to prevent unexpected charges, and use **budget alerts** to monitor your usage against the $200 monthly free credit [Source 1].

**Sources:**
- [Common Errors and Troubleshooting](https://developers.google.com/maps/documentation/javascript/error-messages)
- [Routes API and Directions](https://developers.google.com/maps/documentation/routes/overview)
- [Google Maps Platform Billing and Pricing](https://developers.google.com/maps/billing-and-pricing/pricing)

Use the **Places API (New)** — specifically the `PlaceAutocompleteElement` web component or the `Autocomplete` class with the `Place` class for handling results. The legacy `PlacesService` is being actively replaced and the new API has meaningful advantages [Source 1, Source 2].

Here's why the new API wins:

- **Field masking**: You only pay for the fields you request, reducing cost [Source 2]
- **Promise-based**: No more callback hell — async/await works natively [Source 3]
- **Session tokens**: Still supported and important for cost optimization in both old and new APIs [Source 1]
- **`PlaceAutocompleteElement`**: A modern web component that handles UI concerns for you [Source 1]

## Recommended Implementation

The `PlaceAutocompleteElement` is the most current pattern:

```javascript
// Load the places library
const { PlaceAutocompleteElement } = await google.maps.importLibrary("places");

const placeAutocomplete = new google.maps.places.PlaceAutocompleteElement({
  componentRestrictions: { country: "us" },
});

// Attach to your DOM
document.getElementById("search-container").appendChild(placeAutocomplete);

// Handle place selection
placeAutocomplete.addEventListener("gmp-placeselect", async (event) => {
  const place = event.place;

  // Only fetch the fields you actually need (field masking = cost savings)
  await place.fetchFields({
    fields: ["displayName", "location", "formattedAddress"],
  });

  console.log(place.displayName);
  console.log(place.formattedAddress);
  map.setCenter(place.location);
  map.setZoom(15);
});
```

If you need the older `Autocomplete` widget (more control over the input element), it's still supported and reasonable to use — just make sure you're requesting only the fields you need:

```javascript
const { Autocomplete } = await google.maps.importLibrary("places");

const autocomplete = new Autocomplete(
  document.getElementById("search-input"),
  {
    types: ["geocode", "establishment"],
    componentRestrictions: { country: "us" },
    fields: ["place_id", "geometry", "formatted_address", "name"], // keep this tight
  }
);

autocomplete.addListener("place_changed", () => {
  const place = autocomplete.getPlace();
  if (!place.geometry) {
    console.warn("No geometry returned for selected place.");
    return;
  }
  map.setCenter(place.geometry.location);
  map.setZoom(15);
});
```

## Billing note

Autocomplete sessions are billed at **$2.83 per 1,000 sessions** when using session tokens. Without them, every keystroke is a separate request at the same rate — which adds up fast [Source 5]. The `PlaceAutocompleteElement` handles session token management automatically, which is another reason to prefer it.

